About 48,500 babies have been born since 2013 under the Jubilee government&rsquo;s free maternity services programme in Uasin Gishu county.Details released by State House spokesman Monoah Esipisu indicate the government spent Sh78 million on the programme.Most babies were born at the Moi Teaching and Referral Hospital in Eldoret.&ldquo;The free maternity services initiative has been successful and helped raise deliveries in hospitals by more than 40 per cent. It has also reduced maternal mortality rates,&rdquo; hospital CEO Dr Wilson Aruasa said yesterday.He said medical facilities in rural areas have been equipped, allowing women to access services easily.Aruasa said the government has approved the construction of the new Moi Teaching and Referral Hospital in Eldoret for Sh24 billion. The facility will include a special wing for children.